data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10 (EF Core 10), the Cosmos DB provider threw `InvalidOperationException` on sync LINQ by default, but you could opt back in with sync-over-async:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousQueryExecution(true));
```

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`, etc.) against the Cosmos provider throw `InvalidOperationException` with no workaround.

## What to do

Convert every sync call to its async equivalent:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

Remove the `AllowSynchronousQueryExecution` configuration — it will cause a compile error in EF Core 11.
